  "prompt": "Who are some great but lesser known female Indian freedom fighters?",
  "response": "India's struggle for independence was marked by the bravery and dedication of numerous women who played pivotal roles, many of whom remain lesser-known despite their significant contributions. Here are some remarkable but often overlooked female Indian freedom fighters:\n\n1. **Usha Mehta (1907\u20131987)**\n   \n   Usha Mehta was instrumental during the Quit India Movement of 1942. As the secretary of the Ahmedabad Congress Radio, she managed underground radio broadcasts when all forms of communication were banned by the British. Her efforts helped disseminate vital information and maintain the spirit of resistance among the people. Usha Mehta was arrested in 1943 and spent several years in prison for her activities.\n\n2. **Pritilata Waddedar (1911\u20131932)**\n   \n   A fearless revolutionary from Bengal, Pritilata Waddedar was one of the first women to actively participate in armed resistance against British rule. At just 21, she led an attack on the Peshawar Police Line in 1932, armed with bombs and firearms. Although she was fatally wounded during the operation, her courage inspired many young women to join the freedom struggle.\n\n3. **Durgabai Deshmukh (1909\u20131981)**\n   \n   Durgabai Deshmukh was a multifaceted freedom fighter, social reformer, and politician. She actively participated in the civil disobedience movement and was imprisoned multiple times for her activities. After independence, she played a significant role in framing the Constitution of India and founded the Andhra Pradesh Social Service League, focusing on education and women's empowerment.\n\n4. **Rani Gaidinliu (1915\u20131993)**\n   \n   Rani Gaidinliu was a Naga spiritual and political leader who led the Shewrei Naga revolt against British colonialism in the 1930s. She promoted peace and resistance through traditional beliefs and practices, uniting her people in the fight for autonomy. Her leadership earned her imprisonment and she became a symbol of resistance in the northeastern regions of India.\n\n5. **Jhalkaribai (active during the 1857 Rebellion)**\n   \n   Often hailed as one of the early female warriors, Jhalkaribai fought valiantly alongside her husband during the Indian Rebellion of 1857. She defended her fort in Gaharwal against the British forces, leading her troops with valor and determination. Her bravery became a source of inspiration for many women involved in the rebellion.\n\n6. **Annie Lakshmi Ramanujan (1899\u20131950)**\n   \n   Although more renowned for her contributions to literature and mathematics, Annie Lakshmi Ramanujan was also involved in the freedom movement. She used her intellectual influence to advocate for India's independence and inspired many through her writings and educational initiatives.\n\n7. **Suchitra Sen (Not to be confused with the actress)**\n   \n   An underground freedom fighter, Suchitra Sen played a crucial role in organizing protests and mobilizing women in the northeastern states of India. She worked closely with other activists to strategize movements against British policies, ensuring sustained resistance in her region.\n\nThese women, among many others, exemplify the courage and resilience that fueled India's fight for independence. Their stories, though not as widely recognized, are integral to the rich tapestry of India's freedom movement.",
